{"title_page": "List of 24 Hours of Le Mans winners", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n[[Image:Tom Kristensen 2008.JPG|thumb|right|250px|The most successful participant of all time at Le Mans, Danish driver [[Tom Kristensen (racing driver)|Tom Kristensen]] leads with nine wins (during 1997\u20132013), of which six were consecutive (2000\u20132005)]]\nThe [[24 Hours of Le Mans]] (''24 heures du Mans'') is the world's oldest [[Sports car racing|sports car]] [[Endurance racing (motorsport)|endurance race]] and one of the most famous and influential in motorsports history.\n\nThe overall winners of all events since 1923 are listed here. The race has been run every year since its inception with the exception of 1936, where the race was not run due to [[Great Depression in France#From depression to war|worker strikes]], and 1940 to 1948, due to [[World War II]].  Records for wins are also listed. Lower class wins are not included.\n\nAfter the first 44 events had two drivers per winning entry, the winning entry used three drivers in 1977, which became the winning norm from 1985 onwards. With multiple drivers per winning entry, tempered by some drivers winning more than once, a total of 136 different drivers have won in the [[2019 24 Hours of Le Mans|86 runnings]] of the race.\n\n==Winners==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Drivers\n! Team\n! Car \n! Tyre\n! Laps\n! Distance\n! Championship\n|-\n! [[1923 24 Hours of Le Mans|1923]]\n| {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Andr\u00e9 Lagache]]<br>{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Ren\u00e9 L\u00e9onard]]\n| {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Chenard-Walcker|Chenard & Walcker SA]]\n| [[Chenard-Walcker|Chenard & Walcker]] Sport 3-Litre\n| {{Michelin}}\n| 128\n| 2209.536&nbsp;km\n|\n|-\n! [[1924 24 Hours of Le Mans|1924]]\n| {{flagicon|CAN|1921}} [[John Duff]]<br>{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Frank Clement (racing driver)|Frank Clement]]\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[John Duff|Duff]] & Aldington\n| [[Bentley 3 Litre|Bentley 3 Litre Sport]]\n| {{Dunlop}}\n| 120\n| 2077.341&nbsp;km\n|\n|-\n! [[1925 24 Hours of Le Mans|1925]]\n| {{flagicon|FRA}} [[G\u00e9rard de Courcelles]]<br>{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Andr\u00e9 Rossignol]]\n| {{flagicon|}} ''No Team Name''\n| [[Lorraine-Dietrich]] B3-6\n| {{Dunlop}}\n| 129\n| 2233.982&nbsp;km\n|\n|-\n! [[1926 24 Hours of Le Mans|1926]]\n| {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Robert Bloch (racing driver)|Robert Bloch]]<br>{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Andr\u00e9 Rossignol]]\n| {{flagicon|}} ''No Team Name''\n| [[Lorraine-Dietrich]] B3-6\n| {{Dunlop}}\n| 147\n| 2552.414&nbsp;km\n|\n|-\n! [[1927 24 Hours of Le Mans|1927]]\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Dudley Benjafield]]<br>{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Sammy Davis (racing driver)|Sammy Davis]]\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Bentley|Bentley Motors Ltd.]]\n| [[Bentley 3 Litre|Bentley 3 Litre Super Sport]]\n| {{Dunlop}}\n| 137\n| 2369.807&nbsp;km\n|\n|-\n! [[1928 24 Hours of Le Mans|1928]]\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Woolf Barnato]]<br>{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Bernard Rubin]]\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Bentley|Bentley Motors Ltd.]]\n| [[Bentley 4\u00bd Litre]]\n| {{Dunlop}}\n| 154\n| 2669.272&nbsp;km\n|\n|-\n! [[1929 24 Hours of Le Mans|1929]]\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Woolf Barnato]]<br>{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Tim Birkin|Henry Birkin]]\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Bentley|Bentley Motors Ltd.]]\n| [[Bentley Speed Six]]\n| {{Dunlop}}\n| 174\n| 2843.83&nbsp;km\n|\n|-\n! [[1930 24 Hours of Le Mans|1930]]\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Woolf Barnato]]<br>{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Glen Kidston]]\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Bentley|Bentley Motors Ltd.]]\n| [[Bentley Speed Six]]\n| {{Dunlop}}\n| 179\n| 2930.663&nbsp;km\n|\n|-\n! [[1931 24 Hours of Le Mans|1931]]\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Francis Curzon, 5th Earl Howe|Earl Howe]]<br>{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Tim Birkin|Henry Birkin]]\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Francis Richard Henry Penn Curzon, 5th Earl Howe|Earl Howe]]\n| [[Alfa Romeo 8C|Alfa Romeo 8C 2300]]\n| {{Dunlop}}\n| 184\n| 3017.654&nbsp;km\n|\n|-\n! [[1932 24 Hours of Le Mans|1932]]\n| {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Raymond Sommer]]<br>{{flagicon|ITA|1861}} [[Luigi Chinetti]]\n| {{fla